The game also explicitly takes place in the real world, as Gulliver sails to real world countries and brings you back souvenirs from them. But he also talks about visiting the Mushroom Kingdom from Mario... when Mario is also a video game in Animal Crossing's universe, as you can play the NES version on a cartridge in the first game...

The devs are clearly aware of this, as people in-universe point stuff like this out. Villagers will sometimes remark on how strange it is that their village has no bathrooms, for example. Even so, there are a lot of things that are implied but never explored in depth, like villager romance with each other and you. Idk man.
